body:
A streamlined test is possible:

```csharp
! (objectType.GetInterface("System.Collections.Generic.IDictionary`2", false) is null)
```

And, even though it is an _additional_ test that must be performed, the performance impact is ~~surprisingly small~~:

See the updated benchmarks [below](https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/issues/15204#issuecomment-818235777).

<details>
<summary>Outdated results and outdated benchmark code:</summary>

Here is sample output from running the benchmarks below on my macOS 10.15.7 system with .NET 6.0.100-preview.3.21202.5

```none
Cumulative timings from 1000 runs:
  non-generic, .IsAssignableFrom()   : 00:00:00.0031652
  generic, .GetInterface()           : 00:00:00.0033636
  combined                           : 00:00:00.0035919
Ratio of generic vs. non-generic test : 1.06
Ratio of combined vs. non-generic test: 1.13
```

In repeated runs the ranking of ratios on occasion even reverses (the _combined_ test is reported as faster) or the two ratios are the same. (The input type was chosen so that _both_ tests are indeed performed so that no short-circuiting occurs).

It is possible that my benchmarks (see below) are flawed; I have little experience with profiling C# code.



```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Collections;
using System.Diagnostics;
using System.Dynamic;

namespace demo
{

  class Program
  {
    static TimeSpan timeAction(Action action, int runs)
    {
      var thisProcess = Process.GetCurrentProcess();
      TimeSpan tsBefore, tsAfter, tsTotal = new TimeSpan(0);
      for (var i = 0; i < runs; ++i)
      {
        tsBefore = thisProcess.TotalProcessorTime;
        action.Invoke();
        tsAfter = thisProcess.TotalProcessorTime;
        tsTotal += tsAfter - tsBefore;
      }
      return tsTotal;
    }

    static void Main(string[] args)
    {

      var obj = new ExpandoObject();
      var objectType = obj.GetType();

      string[] descriptions =
      {
        "non-generic, .IsAssignableFrom()",
        "generic, .GetInterface()",
        "combined"
      };

      Action[] actions =
      {
        () => { var isNonGenericDict  = typeof(IDictionary).IsAssignableFrom(objectType); },
        () => { var isGenericDict     = ! (objectType.GetInterface("System.Collections.Generic.IDictionary`2", false) is null); },
        () => { var isEither          = typeof(IDictionary).IsAssignableFrom(objectType) || ! (objectType.GetInterface("System.Collections.Generic.IDictionary`2", false) is null); }
      };

      // Run the commands in isolation first, to level the playing field with
      // respect to one-time initializations, such as loading types on demand.
      foreach (var action in actions) { action.Invoke(); }

      // Run the benchmarks:
      int runs = 1000; 
      List<TimeSpan> timings = new();
      foreach (var action in actions)
      {
        timings.Add(timeAction(action, runs));
      }

      Console.WriteLine($"Cumulative timings from {runs} runs:");
      var i = 0;
      foreach (var ts in timings)
      {
        Console.WriteLine($"  {descriptions[i++].PadRight(35)}: {ts}");
      }
      Console.WriteLine($"Ratio of generic vs. non-generic test : {timings[1] / timings[0]:N2}");
      Console.WriteLine($"Ratio of combined vs. non-generic test: {timings[2] / timings[0]:N2}");

    } // Main()

  } // class

} // namespace
```
</details>

I appreciate the pointer, @SeeminglyScience.

Using BenchmarkDotNet indeed paints a different picture:

```none
|            Method |      Mean |    Error |   StdDev |
|------------------ |----------:|---------:|---------:|
|    TestForGeneric | 167.66 ns | 1.836 ns | 1.627 ns |
| TestForNonGeneric |  11.82 ns | 0.075 ns | 0.071 ns |
|     TestForEither | 183.13 ns | 1.491 ns | 1.322 ns |
```

That is, the combined test takes around 16 times as long as the current, non-generic-interface-only test, on my macOS 10.15.7 machine with .NET 6.0.100-preview.3.21202.5

What that would mean in terms of real-world impact I don't know.

<details>
<summary>Benchmark code based on BenchmarkDotNet</summary>

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections;
using System.Dynamic;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Attributes;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Running;

namespace csbm
{
  public class InterfaceTestBenchmarks
  {

    // A type that implements IDictionary`2, but not also the non-generic IDictionary interface.
    static readonly Type s_typeToInspect = new ExpandoObject().GetType();

    [Benchmark]
    public bool TestForGeneric()
    {
        return ! (s_typeToInspect.GetInterface("System.Collections.Generic.IDictionary`2") is null);
    }
    
    [Benchmark]
    public bool TestForNonGeneric()
    {
        return typeof(IDictionary).IsAssignableFrom(s_typeToInspect);
    }

    [Benchmark]
    public bool TestForEither()
    {
        return typeof(IDictionary).IsAssignableFrom(s_typeToInspect) || ! (s_typeToInspect.GetInterface("System.Collections.Generic.IDictionary`2") is null);
    }

  }
  class Program
  {
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        // For verifying that the tests are correct: Should be False, True, True
        Console.WriteLine(new InterfaceTestBenchmarks().TestForNonGeneric());
        Console.WriteLine(new InterfaceTestBenchmarks().TestForGeneric());
        Console.WriteLine(new InterfaceTestBenchmarks().TestForEither());

        BenchmarkRunner.Run<InterfaceTestBenchmarks>();
    }
  }

}
```
</details>

That actually performs worse than the `.GetInterface("...")` approach (but it outperforms the delegate-based `.FindInterfaces()` approach):

```none
|                                  Method |     Mean |   Error |  StdDev |
|---------------------------------------- |---------:|--------:|--------:|
|          TestForGeneric_GetByNameString | 169.7 ns | 2.37 ns | 2.22 ns |
| TestForGeneric_EnumerateAndCompareTypes | 225.2 ns | 1.53 ns | 1.35 ns |
|           TestForGeneric_FindInterfaces | 283.5 ns | 2.53 ns | 2.37 ns |
```

<details>
<summary>Benchmark code:</summary>

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Dynamic;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Attributes;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Running;

namespace csbm
{
  public class InterfaceTestBenchmarks
  {

    // A type that implements IDictionary`2, but not also the non-generic IDictionary interface.
    static readonly Type s_typeToInspect = typeof(ExpandoObject);

    [Benchmark]
    public bool TestForGeneric_GetByNameString()
    {
        return s_typeToInspect.GetInterface("System.Collections.Generic.IDictionary`2") != null;
    }

    [Benchmark]
    public bool TestForGeneric_EnumerateAndCompareTypes()
    {
     foreach (Type i in s_typeToInspect.GetInterfaces()) 
     { 
         if (i.IsGenericType && i.GetGenericTypeDefinition() == typeof(IEnumerable<>)) return true;
     }
     return false;
    }
    
    [Benchmark]
    public bool TestForGeneric_FindInterfaces()
    {
     return 0 != s_typeToInspect.FindInterfaces((t, o) => t.IsGenericType && t.GetGenericTypeDefinition() == typeof(IEnumerable<>), null).Length;
    }
    
  }
  class Program
  {
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        // For verifying that the tests are correct: Should be True, True, True
        Console.WriteLine(new InterfaceTestBenchmarks().TestForGeneric_GetByNameString());
        Console.WriteLine(new InterfaceTestBenchmarks().TestForGeneric_EnumerateAndCompareTypes());
        Console.WriteLine(new InterfaceTestBenchmarks().TestForGeneric_FindInterfaces());
 
        BenchmarkRunner.Run<InterfaceTestBenchmarks>();
    }
  }

}
```

</detals>

GetEnumerableFromIEnumerableT should return null for IDictionary`2 too so we need to enumerate `obj.GetType().GetInterfaces()` in any case.

```c#
 private static IEnumerable GetEnumerableFromIEnumerableT(object obj) 
 { 
     foreach (Type i in obj.GetType().GetInterfaces()) 
     { 
         if (i.IsGenericType && i.GetGenericTypeDefinition() == typeof(IEnumerable<>) && "it is not IDictionary`2") 
         { 
             return new EnumerableTWrapper(obj, i); 
         } 
     } 
  
     return null; 
 } 
```
